  9  /-! # Local extrema of smooth functions
 10  
 11  ## Main definitions
 12  
 13  In a real normed space `E` we define `pos_tangent_cone_at (s : set E) (x : E)`.
 14  This would be the same as `tangent_cone_at â„â‰¥0 s x` if we had a theory of normed semifields.
 15  This set is used in the proof of Fermat's Theorem (see below), and can be used to formalize
 16  [Lagrange multipliers](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lagrange_multiplier) and/or
 17  [Karushâ€“Kuhnâ€“Tucker conditions](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Karushâ€“Kuhnâ€“Tucker_conditions).
 18  
 19  ## Main statements
 20  
 21  For each theorem name listed below, we also prove similar theorems for `min`, `extr` (if applicable)`,
 22  and `(f)deriv` instead of `has_fderiv`.
 23  
 24  * `is_local_max_on.has_fderiv_within_at_nonpos` : `f' y â‰¤ 0` whenever `a` is a local maximum
 25    of `f` on `s`, `f` has derivative `f'` at `a` within `s`, and `y` belongs to the positive tangent
 26    cone of `s` at `a`.
 27  
 28  * `is_local_max_on.has_fderiv_within_at_eq_zero` : In the settings of the previous theorem, if both
 29    `y` and `-y` belong to the positive tangent cone, then `f' y = 0`.
 30  
 31  * `is_local_max.has_fderiv_at_eq_zero` :
 32    [Fermat's Theorem](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fermat's_theorem_(stationary_points)),
 33    the derivative of a differentiable function at a local extremum point equals zero.
 34  
 35  * `exists_has_deriv_at_eq_zero` :
 36    [Rolle's Theorem](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rolle's_theorem): given a function `f` continuous
 37    on `[a, b]` and differentiable on `(a, b)`, there exists `c âˆˆ (a, b)` such that `f' c = 0`.
 38  
 39  ## Implementation notes
 40  
 41  For each mathematical fact we prove several versions of its formalization:
 42  
 43  * for maxima and minima;
 44  * using `has_fderiv*`/`has_deriv*` or `fderiv*`/`deriv*`.
 45  
 46  For the `fderiv*`/`deriv*` versions we omit the differentiability condition whenever it is possible
 47  due to the fact that `fderiv` and `deriv` are defined to be zero for non-differentiable functions.
